<article>
    <h1>5&#xD;&#xA;Boat Noo&#xAD;dle Ex&#xAD;press</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201108/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-08"><time>2020-11-08</time></a>
        - <span>FOOD &amp; DRINK | LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WHERE</p>
    <p>01-06 Sim Lim Square, 1 Ro­chor Canal Road</p>
    <p>OPEN 10.30am to 9pm daily TEL 9793-3237</p>
    <p>The tables are rick­ety and the round wooden stools are un­com­fort­able, but they lend street cred to Boat Noo­dle Ex­press at Sim Lim Square.</p>
    <p>As its name sug­gests, this is not an eatery to daw­dle over your meal. Ser­vice is brisk.</p>
    <p>The nar­row shop unit is lo­cated at the side of the build­ing, fac­ing Ro­chor Canal Road.</p>
    <p>A queue of cus­tomers forms quickly by noon. Never mind that it is hot and hu­mid. They make a bee­line for a cheap Thai noo­dle fix.</p>
    <p>Co-founder and co-owner of Boat Noo­dle Ex­press, Ms De­siree Goh, 41, went to Thai­land to learn to cook boat noo­dles in 2015.</p>
    <p>The Pork Spe­cial Soup Noo­dles ($6) is pre­pared with a hearty broth us­ing more than 15 in­gre­di­ents, in­clud­ing a spe­cial blend of Thai spices. It re­lies on the flavour of pork bones, en­hanced with Thai light sea­son­ing sauce, with­out ta­ble salt.</p>
    <p>Cus­tomers get a choice of glass noo­dles, mee kia, kway teow, bee hoon or tang hoon. Go for the orig­i­nal Thai glass noo­dles.</p>
    <p>You can choose the level of spice: non-spicy, less spicy, nor­mal spicy or ex­tra spicy.</p>
    <p>Un­for­tu­nately, the Pork Tom Yum Dry Noo­dles ($6.50) is lack­lus­tre. The noo­dles are slightly over­cooked and bland.</p>
    <p>Skip that and opt for the side dishes in­stead – the Thai Fish Cakes ($3.90), Crispy Chicken Wings ($4.90) and Thai Pork Crack­ling ($3.90) will do nicely.</p>
    <p>Al­though these are not made in­house, Ms Goh takes care in sourc­ing her sup­plies from Thai­land.</p>
    <p>The fish cakes are bouncy and in­cred­i­bly aro­matic with kaf­fir lime leaves. They taste even bet­ter than some house­made ones at other Thai eater­ies.</p>
    <p>The pork crack­ling is light and crisp, with nary a trace of ran­cid­ness. The chicken wings are flavour­ful and re­main crispy even if you choose to slurp your noo­dles first.</p>

